metadata.name: Collage #153
metadata.description:
Inspired by traditional Japanese wagami design. We use the iconic patterns of our previous projects to recreate this artwork. All the patterns are generated first and then used to build the scene. 

In this project Aluan brings his delicate texture from his 'Chaos' series, Jinyao brings his beloved pattern from the 'Cloud' series and Wen brings his iconic pattern from the 'Maze'. 'Collage' is not just about mixing our style, but it is also about finding harmony among all the elements. 'Collage' is also about working together, in that we can create something that's difficult to achieve or imagine if we were working alone.

Each piece contains the patterns of all the 3 artists, each artist has a certain number of patterns with different colors. Depending which artist you get, his pattern will be shown as the primary color theme while the pattern of the other 2 artists turns into grayscale to make the primary pattern with color stand out. 

There are 7 different scenes included in this project, which are : Mountains, Waves, Lake, Hexagons, Tetrapods, Chrysanthemums and Lotus. We took great inspiration from the traditional Japanese design, and we discovered these are some of the most common elements in it. Therefore we decide to use them and reimagine them by mixing our patterns. 

The title 'Collage' doesn't only apply to the visual style, but also to the code as well. In this project we mixed p5.js and Vanilla JS. While Aluan and Jinyao work with their patterns in p5. Wen gathered the patterns and recreated the full scene in Vanilla JS.

metadata.name: Skravert #104
metadata.description:
‘Skravert’ - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‘The act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area’.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021

metadata.name: Pastoral Palettes #48
metadata.description:
Pastoral Palettes showcases 93 beautiful hand tuned palettes in a generative pastoral setting. The palettes themselves pay homage to great paintings from the past up to the present. Isolating the palettes in this way brings out the artistic genius of the underlying artwork in a unique way. The palette name in the features contains the painting and artist.

The algorithmic parts of Pastoral Palettes use many techniques to create the scene and generate the ground, sky, trees, and shrubbery. Using random perlin noise for the placement ensures a more natural looking scene. The sky is a gradient composed from the palette. Each blade of grass is drawn individually using perlin noise to create the color pattern in the grass. Each tree and shrub is randomly constructed and colored using color blending in the transition colors. The grass generation is the most computationally expensive and the density can be adjusted with the arrow keys, see below.

The mint size is relatively small in relation to the number of palettes, so to ensure that all palettes get generated at least once, we are including 2 palettes for each mint.

Each mint of Pastoral Palettes comes with sunlight and moonlight views, toggled with the 'f' key. The palettes look strikingly different for each view - you can choose which one you like best.

Variations:

 - Each palette has an equal chance of being minted. Since the mint size is so small compared to the number of palettes, there is a high chance of getting a rare palette. 
 - 2% chance of getting 5 palettes instead of the default of 2. 
 - 10% chance of getting a sun/moon in the sky.
 - Each layout will be entirely unique.

Pastoral Palettes is responsive and looks great on any size display. They look especially good on large displays of 2K, 4K, and even 8K.

'f' flips between sunlight and moonlight views.
'p' cycles through the palettes.
's' saves an image in the exact size of the current display.
'up/down arrow' adjusts the grass density. Denser grass may look better at some resolutions, but takes considerably longer to render, particularly on large displays.

metadata.name: Antiflow #482
metadata.description:
"Opposites are not contradictory but complementary." - Niels Bohr

The concept of yin and yang is an ancient philosophy about how opposing forces are not only complementary but actually give rise to each other. This idea reverberates through nature, art, and life itself. Now it is at the heart of modern physics. Perhaps this is a fundamental law of nature baked into the very fabric of existence.

Antiflow is an exploration of how balanced complexity can arise from chaos by harnessing the dynamic interplay of opposing forces. To that end we were inspired to create this wildly unique set by mixing modern physics concepts with abstract expressionism and retro 3D primitives.

The aspect ratio is 3:2 to facilitate poster size prints and device wallpapers. Results are presented without borders, noise, or other effects to allow for maximum detail. Feel free to rotate in whatever direction you choose for the best display.

Press "S" to save at a higher definition.

metadata.name: Solace #27
metadata.description:
Solace is an algorithm that generates artworks of sand dunes. It draws hundreds of thousands of tiny points according to a probability distribution calculated from the positions of the dunes.

The logic to divide the dunes into light and dark sides is simple, but produces some interesting chaotic behaviour. These are details that weren't hard-coded but emerge organically, such as the patterns on the spines of the dunes or the stripes around their bases.

Please note that the algorithm can take some time to run, especially when the number of dunes is high.

Created by lunarean.

metadata.name: Unfolded #272
metadata.description:
A plane is repeatedly folded over itself, choosing creases either at random, or according to some pattern (like a grid). These creases form the boundaries of the individual textured tiles.

Once the folds are complete, they are undone in reverse order, recreating the original plane. With each unfolding, the orientation of each crease (as a mountain or a valley), and each tile (facing up or down) is recorded as a sequence of 1s and 0s. Tiles are colored and textured according to similarities in these binary sequences, giving rise to subtle symmetries and repetitions.

Written in vanilla JS & HTML5 Canvas.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: <iframes> #57
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110

metadata.name: Ambient Landscapes synthesizer #67
metadata.description:
Ambient Landscapes is an audiovisual modular synthesizer.

Each edition has unique base sequence, scale, parameter combination, and visual landscape.

The generation principle is based on aliasing technique - a base sequence is modulated to hearable range, then passed through an effect chain and demodulated back to a sequence. Passed through quantizer this gives an almost infinite continuous field of base melody variations, completely controllable by parameters of the effect chain. Besides that, one also can control pitch, tempo, noise amount, filters and shape of the second melody by dragging the stars in the constellations. Each star can also be toggled to drift and evolve in automatic mode.

Interface:
- click / space to start
- mouse to drag dots and change params
- "e" while dragging to toggle dot auto evolution
- "v" to unfold to full screen (also gives better performance)
- "r" to reset dots to initial positions

Engine: @ferluht
Generative patch design: @alexeev
January 2022
